#: ../../source/docs/hardware/sensors/ultrasonics-hardware.rst:31
msgid "Caveats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/hardware/sensors/ultrasonics-hardware.rst:33
msgid ""
"Ultrasonic sensors are generally quite easy to use, however there are a "
"few caveats.  As ultrasonics work by measuring the time between the pulse"
" and its echo, they generally measure distance only to the *closest* "
"target in their range.  Thus, it is extremely important to pick a the "
"right sensor for the job.  The documentation for ultrasonic sensors will "
"generally include a picture of the \"beam pattern\" that shows the shape "
"of the \"window\" in which the ultrasonic will detect a target - pay "
"close attention to this when selecting your sensor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/hardware/sensors/ultrasonics-hardware.rst:35
msgid ""
"Ultrasonic sensors are also susceptible to interference from other "
"ultrasonic sensors.  In order to minimize this, the roboRIO can run ping-"
"response ultrasonics in a \"round-robin\" fashion - however, in "
"competition, there is no sure way to ensure that interference from "
"sensors mounted on other robots does not occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/hardware/sensors/ultrasonics-hardware.rst:37
msgid ""
"Finally, ultrasonics may not be able to detect objects that absorb sound "
"waves, or that redirect them in strange ways.  Thus, they work best for "
"detecting hard, flat objects."
msgstr ""

